Afdød","1385–Male":"1385–Afdød","1385–Female":"1385–Afdød","1402–Male":"1402–Afdød","1405–Male":"1405–Afdød","1405–Female":"1405–Afdød","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1350–Male":"1350–Afdød","1350–Female":"1350–Afdød","1402":"1402","1385":"1385","April 1409":"april 1409","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","about 1385":"omkring 1385","1480":"1480","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Tyskland","Reutlingen, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Reutlingen, Württemberg, Tyskland","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Tyskland"},"nl":{"about 1385–":"circa 1385–Overleden","1385–Male":"1385–Overleden","1385–Female":"1385–Overleden","1402–Male":"1402–Overleden","1405–Male":"1405–Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1350–Male":"1350–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1402":"1402","1385":"1385","April 1409":"april 1409","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","about 1385":"circa 1385","1480":"1480","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Duitsland","Reutlingen, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Reutlingen, Württemberg, Duitsland","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Duitsland"},"en":{"about 1385–":"about 1385–Deceased","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1402–Male":"1402–Deceased","1405–Male":"1405–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1402":"1402","1385":"1385","April 1409":"April 1409","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","about 1385":"about 1385","1480":"1480","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Saxony, Germany","Reutlingen, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Reutlingen, Württemberg, Germany","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bauer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Fritz, Helmut, Heinz, Manfred, Franz, Gerhard, Johannes, Wolfgang.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): status name for a peasant or nickname meaning ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, from Middle High German <i>(ge)būr</i>, Middle Low German <i>būr</i>, denoting an occupant of a <i>būr</i>, a small dwelling or building. This word later fell together with Middle High German <i>būwære</i>, an agent noun from Old High German <i>būwan</i> ‘to cultivate’, later also (at first in Low German dialects) ‘to build’. The precise meaning of the Jewish surname, which is of later formation, is unclear. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic status names or surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Agricola","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Algert, Cornelis.  German Aloys, Otto.","German and Dutch: humanistic surname, a translation into Latin of German   Bauer   and Dutch   Boer   ‘farmer’."]},{"name":"Bauerlein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Gunther.","German (<b>Bäuerlein</b>): standardized diminutive of   Bauer  , originally occurring in southern dialects as <b>Bäuerle</b> (see   Bauerle  ),   Beuerle  , and   Beyerle  ."]},{"name":"Baur","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Uli, Ulrich, Alfons, Arno, Erwin, Friedrich, Fritz, Urs, Wilhelm, Wolfgang.","South German: variant of   Bauer   ‘peasant’ or ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Ankenbauer","meanings":["South German (mainly Bavaria): from Middle High German <i>anken</i> ‘butter’ + <i>būr</i> ‘farmer’ (see   Bauer  ), hence an occupational name for a dairy farmer. Alternatively, the first element may be a topographic term, <i>Anke</i>, meaning ‘slight rise in the ground’, or an old term <i>ank</i> ‘watery’, hence ‘farmer with fields in a wet area’."]},{"name":"Bierle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto.","South German: from a diminutive of   Bauer  , an unrounded form of Alemannic <b>Bürle</b> (compare   Buehrle  )."]},{"name":"Beurer","meanings":["(2010: NA)","South German: habitational name for someone from any of various places called Beuren, from Old High German <i>būr</i> ‘small dwelling’ (see   Bauer  )."]},{"name":"Bauerle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Albrecht, Helmut, Horst, Lothar, Merwin, Otto.","South German (<b>Bäuerle</b>): from a Swabian diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Bauers","meanings":["German: variant of   Bauer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or from a first part of an original compound name (e.g.   Bauersfeld  )."]},{"name":"Beuerle","meanings":["South German: diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Baumann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Otto, Gerhard, Ernst, Heinz, Guenter, Armin, Dieter, Erna, Friedrich.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): status name for a peasant or a nickname meaning ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, from Middle High German <i>būman</i>, German <i>Baumann</i> ‘peasant’ (see   Bauer  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Poland, and some other European countries. Compare   Bauman   and   Bowman  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Josef","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":[", Dutch, Scandinavian, and Czech spelling of   Joseph  , now also in use in the English‐speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Joseph","meanings":["form of the biblical Hebrew name <i>Yosef</i>, meaning ‘(God) shall add (another son)’. This was borne by the favourite son of Jacob, whose brothers became jealous of him and sold him into slavery (Genesis 37). He was taken to Egypt, where he rose to become chief steward to Pharaoh, and was eventually reconciled to his brothers when they came to buy corn during a seven-year famine (Genesis 43–7). In the New Testament <i>Joseph</i> is the name of the husband of the Virgin Mary. It is also borne by a rich Jew, Joseph of Arimathea (Matthew 27:57; Mark 15:43; Luke 23:50; John 19:38), who took Jesus down from the Cross, wrapped him in a shroud, and buried him in a rock tomb. According to medieval legend, Joseph of Arimathea brought the Holy Grail to Britain. The name was uncommon in Britain in the Middle Ages but was revived in the mid 16th century and had become popular by the 1630s, remaining so ever since."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Josef Bauer was born about 1385, in Saxony, Germany, his father, Bauer, was 36 and his mother, Bauer, was 36. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Bauer."},"et":{"about 1385–":"umbes 1385–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1402":"1402","1385":"1385","April 1409":"aprill 1409","1350":"1350","1409":"1409","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1480":"1480","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Saksamaa","Reutlingen, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Reutlingen, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"about 1385–":"noin 1385–Kuollut","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1402–Male":"1402–Kuollut","1405–Male":"1405–Kuoll